#T_SP=webanno.custom.Referent|entity|infstat|salience|identity
#T_RL=webanno.custom.Coref|type|BT_webanno.custom.Referent
#Text=Proof
#Text=If the sets S and T considered are empty or singletons , the theorem holds vacuously or trivially .
#Text=Thus assume S and T each contain at least two elements .
#Text=Let U = ( S , ⪯ S ) ∪ ( T , ⪯ T )
#Text=Define the following relation ⪯ on U : ∀ x , y ∈ U : x ⪯ y if and only if : x , y ∈ S : x ⪯ S y or : x , y ∈ T : x ⪯ T y or : x ∈ S , y ∈ T
#Text=We claim that ⪯ is a well - ordering .
#Text=First , we show it is a total ordering .
#Text=Checking in turn each of the criteria for a total ordering :
#Text=Reflexivity
#Text=If x = y , they 're necessarily both in S or T simultaneously .
#Text=Reflexivity then follows from ⪯ S and x ⪯ T being reflexive , as they are both orderings .
#Text=Transitivity
#Text=Let x , y , z ∈ U .
#Text=If x , y , z ∈ S or x , y , z ∈ T simultaneously , then ⪯ is transitive by the transitivity of ⪯ S and ⪯ T .
#Text=Suppose x , y ∈ S and z ∈ T .
#Text=Let x ⪯ y and y ⪯ z .
#Text=Then x ⪯ z because x ∈ S and y ∈ T .
#Text=Suppose x ∈ S and y , z ∈ T .
#Text=Then x ⪯ z also because x ∈ S and y ∈ T .
#Text=Thus ⪯ is transitive .
#Text=Antisymmetry
#Text=Let x ⪯ y and y ⪯ x .
#Text=If x , y ∈ S then x = y by the antisymmetry of ⪯ S .
#Text=Likewise if x , y ∈ T .
#Text=If x ∈ S and y ∈ T , then y ∈ S and x ∈ T as well .
#Text=Thus x = y from the antisymmetry of ⪯ S or ⪯ T .
#Text=Conclude that ⪯ is a total ordering .
#Text=To show ⪯ is a well - ordering , consider a non-empty set X ⊆ U .
#Text=Then either : X ∩ S = ∅ or : X ∩ T = ∅ or : X ∩ S is non-empty and X ∩ T is non-empty .
#Text=In the first case , X ⊆ T , by Intersection with Complement is Empty iff Subset .
#Text=Then X has a smallest element defined by ⪯ T .
#Text=In the second case , X ⊆ S , also by Intersection with Complement is Empty iff Subset .
#Text=Then X has a smallest element defined by ⪯ S .
#Text=In the third case , the smallest element of X ∖ T is an element of S .
#Text=Thus it precedes any element of T by the definition of ⪯ .
#Text=The smallest element of X ∖ T , which is a subset of S , is guaranteed to exist by the well - ordering on S .
#Text=This smallest element is then also the smallest element of ( X ∖ T ) ∪ T = X .
#Text=Thus ⪯ is a well - ordering on S ∪ T . □
#Text=Consider the mapping : k : ( T , ⪯ T ) → ( U , ⪯ ) : k ( α ) = α
#Text=Then k is strictly increasing , by the construction of ⪯ .
#Text=Thus there is a strictly increasing mapping from T to U .
#Text=From Strictly Increasing Mapping Between Wosets Implies Order Isomorphism , T is order isomorphic to U or an initial segment of U .
#Text=Let Ix denote the initial segment in U determined by x , according to k .
#Text=Note that Ix = Ik ( x ) , because k ( x ) = x .
#Text=Suppose x ∈ S .
#Text=Then Ix ⊆ S because ⪯ is a well - ordering .
#Text=Thus there is an order isomorphism from T to Ix in S .
#Text=Suppose x = min T , the smallest element of T .
#Text=Then every element of S strictly precedes x , as x is in T .
#Text=Also , x precedes every element of T , so Ix ≠ T .
#Text=Thus there is an order isomorphism from T to all of S .
#Text=Suppose x ∈ T and x ≠ min T .
#Text=Then Ix defines an initial segment in T .
#Text=Also , every element of S strictly precedes x , as x is in T .
#Text=Thus there is an order isomorphism from an initial segment of T to all of S .
#Text=The cases are distinct by Well - Ordered Class is not Isomorphic to Initial Segment . ■
